"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from the Middle English personal name <i>Tibble</i>, a pet form of   Theobald  .","variant of   Deeble  .","English:"],"variants":[{"name":"Dible","meanings":["English: variant of   Dibble  .","Altered form of German   Deibel   or   Deubel  ."]},{"name":"Theobald","meanings":["German and English: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>theud</i> ‘people, race’ + <i>bald</i> ‘bold, brave’. The English surname represents a learned form, re-created from French <i>Théobald</i>. The usual medieval forms of the name in English and German were <i>Tebald</i> and <i>Tibalt</i> (Old French <i>Teobaud</i>, <i>Tibaut</i>). Compare   Dewald   and   Diebold  ."]},{"name":"Dipple","meanings":["English: variant of   Dibble   (compare   Tipple  ).","Americanized form of German   Dippel  .","History: It was Philip Dippel from Prussia (Germany), whose name was respelled <i>Dipple</i> after he immigrated to the US in the 1830s. He settled in CA in 1849."]},{"name":"Deeble","meanings":["English: (i) nickname from Old French and Anglo-Norman French  <i>deable</i>,  <i>deble</i>,  <i>diable</i>,  <i>dieble</i>,  <i>daiable</i>,  <i>daible</i> ‘devil’. The name may have been interchangeable with the synonymous Middle English  <i>devel</i>;  See  Deaville   (2) and compare John Devill, 1495 in   PROB 11   (North Petherton, Somerset) with the 1590 bearer cited below. (ii) nickname, perhaps from Old French  <i>debile</i> ‘weak, feeble’ (Latin  <i>dēbilis</i>), though the word is not recorded in Anglo-Norman French or Middle English and it would not account for spellings in  <i>-ia-</i> or  <i>-a-</i>. (iii) variant of   Dibble   (1) with lengthening and lowering of /i/ to /e:/, but excluding spellings in  <i>-ia-</i> or  <i>-a-</i>. It is likely that several originally distinct names have become confused."]}]},{"name":"Benedict","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Church Latin <i>benedictus</i> ‘blessed’. This was the name of the saint (  <i>c.</i>480– <i>c.</i>550 ) who composed the Benedictine rule of Christian monastic life that is still followed in essence by all Western orders. He was born near Spoleto in Umbria, central Italy. After studying in Rome, he went to live as a hermit at Subiaco, and later organized groups of followers and imitators into monastic cells. In  <i>c.</i>529  he moved to Monte Cassino, where he founded the great monastery that is still the centre of the Benedictine order. His rule is simple, restrained, and practical.  See also  Bennett ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":39,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":48,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Benedict Dibble was born in 1510, in West Bagborough, Somerset, England. He had at least 2 sons with Joan Cullurd. He died in 1562, in his hometown, at the age of 52."},"et":{"1510–1562":"1510–1562","1511–1580":"1511–1580","1523–1582":"1523–1582","1534–1582":"1534–1582","1558":"1558","1523":"1523","1534":"1